### 🔷 1. The Three Core Operational Constraints of LLMs

These three constraints shape ALL AI-native development decisions. Knowing them explains WHY agents are designed the way they are.

| # | Constraint | What It Means | Design Implication |
|---|---|---|---|
| **1** | **Statelessness** | LLMs have no memory between sessions — every conversation starts fresh | Agents need external memory systems (databases, vector stores) to persist context |
| **2** | **Probabilistic Outputs** | LLMs don't compute deterministic answers — they predict the most likely next token | You cannot guarantee exact outputs; validation, testing & guardrails become essential |
| **3** | **Context Limits** | LLMs can only process a fixed window of text at once (the context window) | Long workflows must be chunked; important info must be actively managed within the window |

> 🔑 These constraints are not bugs — they are fundamental properties of transformer-based LLMs. Good agent design works *around* them, not against them.

